So, in order for the permutation to be picked up in exactly two passes, there must exist a way to split the permutation into two increasing sequences. But as we saw in the example [2,1,3,4,5,...], the permutation cannot be split into two increasing sequences because the first element is larger than the second. However, the permutation can be picked up in two passes because the first pass picks up the increasing sequence [2,3,4,...], and the second pass picks up [1]. So in this case, the permutation is not the concatenation of two increasing sequences, but it can still be picked up in two passes. Wait, so my previous reasoning is incorrect.
